## A4 Boss-First Execution Architecture
**Status:** approved
**Tags:** stack:backend, module:relay
**Depends on:** G6

The default workflow for AI assistants requires human approval at every step. This treats the human as a peer reviewer. AutoForge treats the human as a boss who delegates and expects results. GSD mode shifts the default from "ask for permission" to "ask for forgiveness" — the AI executes autonomously and only interrupts the boss when blocked.

```mermaid
graph LR
    A[Boss Request] --> B{Assistant classify}
    B -->|QUESTION| C[Answer & Stop]
    B -->|DIRECT| D[Coder]
    B -->|NEW_GOAL| E[Advisor]
    E -->|GSD| F{GoalGate}
    F -->|Auto| G[Architect]
    G --> H[Planner]
    H --> I[Coder]
    I --> J{Tests pass?}
    J -->|No| I
    J -->|Yes| K[Reviewer]
    K --> L[Documenter]
    L --> M[Report to Boss]
    F -->|Check mode| N[Human Review]
    N --> G
```

| Approach | Pros | Cons |
|---|---|---|
| GSD default, Check opt-in | Boss is productive; AI does the work | AI may build wrong thing confidently |
| Check default, GSD opt-in | Boss reviews every step | Boss is a bottleneck; loses async value |
| Hybrid (GSD with auto-drifts) | Balance of speed and safety | More complex routing logic |

- Positive: Boss gives one order, receives one report.
- Positive: Reviewer acts as internal QA, not an external gate.
- Negative: If Advisor writes bad Goals, everything downstream is wrong.
- Mitigation: GoalGate is the one required human gate in GSD mode. Advisor uses medium/strong model.


