## A8 Unified Provider & Runtime Architecture
**Status:** done
**Tags:** stack:backend, module:provider
**Depends on:** G14, G15

Two separate AI provider implementations (ai.rs for simple chat, forge/ai.rs for tool-enabled chat) created maintenance burden and duplicated SSE parsing logic. The unified provider/ module consolidates both into a single ClaudeProvider with two streaming modes, backed by a robust incremental SSE parser ported from auto-code-rs.

```mermaid
graph TB
    subgraph "Entry Points"
        CLI[CLI REPL] -->|chat_turn| P[ClaudeProvider]
        WEB[Web API] -->|chat_stream| P
        RLY[Relay Turn] -->|chat_turn| P
    end
    subgraph "Provider Layer"
        P --> SSE[SseParser]
        P --> CFG[load_api_config]
    end
    subgraph "Runtime"
        CM[ContextManager]
        SES[Session Persistence]
        PM[PermissionPolicy]
    end
    subgraph "Tools"
        TR[ToolRegistry]
        TE[ToolError]
    end

    CLI --> CM
    CLI --> TR
    CLI --> PM
    WEB --> TR
    RLY --> TR
```

| Approach | Pros | Cons |
|---|---|---|
| Unified provider/ module (chosen) | Single source of truth, DRY, easy to add providers | All consumers must migrate imports |
| Keep ai.rs + forge/ai.rs separate | No migration needed | Duplicate SSE logic, divergent error handling |
| Trait-based provider abstraction | Pluggable providers | Over-engineered for single-provider use case |

- Positive: Single SSE parser handles both `\r\n\r\n` and `\n\n` frame delimiters.
- Positive: ToolError enum provides structured error classification instead of raw String.
- Positive: Runtime infrastructure (ContextManager, Session, PermissionPolicy) available to both CLI and web modes.
- Negative: OpenAI provider not yet ported (only Claude supported currently).
- Mitigation: provider/ module is structured to accept additional providers without architectural changes.

