## A11 AutoDown Editor — Tiptap-Based WYSIWYG Architecture
**Status:** draft
**Tags:** stack:frontend, module:editor
**Depends on:** G19

AutoForge needs a block-based WYSIWYG editor that natively supports Markdown serialization and can be extended with custom Vue components for AutoDown-specific blocks. Tiptap is the only evaluated framework that satisfies all constraints simultaneously: it is headless (no forced UI), has first-class Vue 3 integration via `VueNodeViewRenderer`, provides a native ProseMirror block model, and includes a dedicated `@tiptap/markdown` extension with per-extension `parseMarkdown`/`renderMarkdown` hooks. Novel.sh demonstrates that wrapping Tiptap into a product-grade editor is viable — we adapt its pattern (headless primitives + styled composition) to Vue 3's Composition API without Jotai or React-specific libraries.


```mermaid
graph TD
    subgraph Frontend
        A[AutoDownEditor.vue] --> B[Tiptap Editor]
        B --> C[ProseMirror EditorView]
        C --> D[Block Nodes]
        D --> E[Vue NodeViews]
        E --> F[CalloutBlock.vue]
        E --> G[MathBlock.vue]
        E --> H[MermaidBlock.vue]
        E --> I[SpecRefBlock.vue]
        B --> J[SlashCommand Extension]
        B --> K[BubbleMenu Extension]
        B --> L[DragHandle Extension]
        B --> M[Markdown Extension]
        M --> N[marked tokenizer]
    end
    subgraph Persistence
        O[WikiPage.content] -->|parse| A
        A -->|serialize| O
    end
```


| Approach | Pros | Cons |
|---|---|---|
| **Tiptap + Vue 3** (chosen) | Headless, Vue-native, markdown built-in, large extension ecosystem | Bundle size ~150KB+ for core + extensions |
| **Native ContentEditable** | Zero dependencies, full control | Must rebuild block model, drag/drop, markdown parser from scratch |
| **CodeMirror 6** | Excellent for code, modular | Flat document model, not block-oriented; poor WYSIWYG image/table support |
| **Lexical (Meta)** | Modern, collaborative-ready | React-first; Vue integration is community-maintained and immature |

- Positive: Custom blocks are real Vue components — reactive, interactive, testable.
- Positive: Markdown round-trip is solved by Tiptap; no custom parser needed for Phase 1.
- Positive: Extension system means adding a new block type does not touch core editor code.
- Negative: Bundle size increase requires code-splitting the editor into a lazy-loaded chunk.
- Negative: ProseMirror has a learning curve for developers implementing custom node views.

